WEBVTT

00:02.663 --> 00:03.364
Here we go.

00:03.384 --> 00:03.685
Okay.

00:04.906 --> 00:12.978
You see, I'll ask you a question, Bill Stolman, we're at the Shiny Library, and I always ask you how you describe the focus of the collection.

00:13.740 --> 00:22.232
And I start by talking my way around the room with manuscripts and early printed books and human books, and then Bibles, it works.

00:22.252 --> 00:28.241
And, I mean, you can see Bibles in a number of different languages.

00:28.261 --> 00:28.722
I mean, you know, in...

00:30.541 --> 00:32.042
Greek and that kind of thing.

00:32.062 --> 00:41.250
And then we get into more Bibles, and then it moves quickly into Renaissance material, particularly Reformation and Luther.

00:43.172 --> 00:45.474
And then there are funny kind of chunks.

00:45.534 --> 00:51.519
There's a kind of reference chunk in there that I very rarely use.

00:51.539 --> 01:00.447
You remember that, I mean, this was a library when his father had it, but it was out in Titusville that had no major reference library near it.

01:00.730 --> 01:06.616
So there are kind of chunks of reference works that, if it had always been here, wouldn't be here.

01:06.636 --> 01:10.940
They'd be in Princeton, and they'd just go next door to use them.

01:10.960 --> 01:12.962
And then the next alcove is American.

01:13.242 --> 01:14.664
These are called alcoves?

01:14.684 --> 01:14.904
Yeah.

01:16.426 --> 01:19.188
Go ahead, you can just talk, and I'm just going to take a few notes when I speak.

01:19.228 --> 01:28.898
The next alcove is American, and that's where the early American printing is, and that's where the grant material is, the Civil War.

01:29.722 --> 01:35.249
And then the next album is Further American, South America's work.

01:38.473 --> 01:45.422
And then the second and last album is kind of great books in general sense.

01:45.482 --> 01:54.673
That's where Locke and there's Tristan Shandy and Faust and that kind of thing.

01:55.074 --> 01:57.557
These are first firsts, right?

01:57.577 --> 01:57.737
Yeah.

01:58.223 --> 02:02.347
You see, but there's a kind of funny, I mean, there's a lost cave with all the books.

02:02.427 --> 02:07.492
I mean, there's the later editions of Bunyan and other works about Bunyan.

02:07.512 --> 02:18.563
There's the thing that Einstein first appeared in, reporting on the, you know, theory of relativity.

02:18.603 --> 02:21.006
You know, Smith and Locke and that kind of thing.

02:21.326 --> 02:24.349
And then you get into, you know, something that's kind of ordinary.

02:24.683 --> 02:27.708
The Dictionary of National Biography and books.

02:27.728 --> 02:44.914
And then the final one tends to be Voyages of Discovery, with a particular emphasis on Mexico and America, and then you get into Mexico.

02:44.934 --> 02:46.656
That's spectacular.

02:46.676 --> 02:52.986
You would say the actual focus of the collection probably was Mr. Shady's father, not the grandfather.

02:53.219 --> 03:18.450
I mean, it was his, the story that they've seen him probably write a couple of times was that his father came to Princeton and heard somewhere in a Western CIS class that the two events which, the two greatest events in the history of the world, which is one of those things only a professor and a first year Western CIS can say, was the discovery of America and the discovery of the printing press.

03:19.004 --> 03:23.671
No, I suspect it was a class on, you know, 15th century or something.

03:23.831 --> 03:36.529
Those were the two things, and so those were the things that he began thinking about, and how the two of them occurred, you know, within 50 years of one another, and what it was that people were doing in that class.

03:36.549 --> 03:40.996
The family, what makes this all possible, of course, is Pennsylvania oil, is that right?

03:41.757 --> 03:45.162
Did that continue through the generations, or did they diversify?

03:45.522 --> 03:46.163
I'm not too sure.

03:46.183 --> 03:48.066
I'm not sure either.

03:49.025 --> 03:56.495
I mean, I... His father... This is not all that important, but I'm just... No, I mean, I think they must have diversified.

03:56.515 --> 03:59.219
It certainly is out of his hands at this point.

03:59.259 --> 04:07.110
I mean, in the sense that he has bankers and money managers in New York with whom he taught, I think, every day.

04:07.790 --> 04:11.916
But, I mean... Ask him what he does professionally.

04:12.076 --> 04:13.638
What would you say, investor?

04:13.658 --> 04:15.621
No, he'd say he's a musicologist.

04:15.641 --> 04:17.604
Really?

04:17.624 --> 04:18.525
And this is how he is?

04:19.012 --> 04:34.636
Yeah, I mean, he would say, I just did a CV for him, because somebody's been nominated for the membership in the American Philosophical Society.

04:34.736 --> 04:41.847
I mean, I'll tell you, he would never tell you, you can't repeat it.

04:41.867 --> 04:46.133
I mean, somebody wants money for something.

04:46.433 --> 04:48.395
He graduated from Princeton in 36.

04:48.435 --> 04:51.058
This is great because I don't want to waste his time.

04:51.999 --> 05:04.791
He then, let me get the things I'll get you.

05:04.811 --> 05:08.055
In 1940, he got a master's in music from Columbia.

05:09.776 --> 05:15.462
And from 1940 to 42, he taught at Cornell in the music department there.

05:18.192 --> 05:21.997
So his adding to the collection in those areas is a natural.

05:22.077 --> 05:23.779
He's a natural as far as he, yeah.

05:24.580 --> 05:30.587
And then, I mean, the TV goes 46 to 80, he was director of the Bach aria group.

05:31.548 --> 05:33.410
So he would say he was a musicologist.

05:35.133 --> 05:37.415
And there's no problem with my asking him that.

05:37.435 --> 05:39.698
No, no.

05:39.718 --> 05:45.465
I'm really looking for impressions, feelings, you know, what it's like to come in here.

05:46.070 --> 05:48.193
This is his.

05:49.315 --> 05:54.403
And that's why they go through that little funny song and dance where they renounce all of this.

05:54.423 --> 05:56.145
I mean, they never actually came in without knocking.

05:56.586 --> 05:59.951
Because, I mean, somehow they've worked out an arrangement with Prince's.

05:59.971 --> 06:03.116
This is his library, and you're on private property.

06:03.797 --> 06:05.820
Now, technically, you may not, but they have to.

06:05.840 --> 06:07.302
It's like an embassy or something.

06:08.311 --> 06:10.514
like the Vatican seal.

06:10.734 --> 06:12.036
Exactly, exactly.

06:12.056 --> 06:16.722
I mean, you don't, I mean, they all, the secretaries always, I told them to don't bother, just come on in.

06:16.803 --> 06:18.004
I'm sure it's been etched.

06:18.525 --> 06:19.727
But they always stop.

06:22.590 --> 06:28.398
Tell me a little bit about yourself, Phil, how you've come to this position.

06:29.220 --> 06:34.707
I was, I have a doctorate in medieval studies, and

06:35.817 --> 06:46.108
did university administration for four years in Toronto, University of Toronto, at Victoria College, and then taught for a couple of years at the University of Windsor.

06:47.249 --> 06:51.354
And, I mean, I was doing administration because the job market was tight.

06:51.374 --> 06:52.094
Are you Canadian?

06:52.134 --> 06:54.237
Yeah, I'm a Canadian citizen.

06:56.539 --> 07:03.066
And I got this job teaching, a 10-year-old student job, and I bought a house, and I thought I was at the University of Windsor, and I thought I was there for that.

07:03.947 --> 07:04.828
And then he called.

07:05.348 --> 07:07.830
Did you know who he was?

07:08.211 --> 07:09.432
Yeah, I know who he was.

07:09.552 --> 07:12.755
I'd been down and used the library.

07:12.775 --> 07:13.515
He wasn't here.

07:13.535 --> 07:16.058
I didn't meet him on that occasion.

07:16.078 --> 07:22.784
I met him at a Library of Congress in Poland on 15th century.

07:22.824 --> 07:32.092
But he was looking for a librarian because Minor Bryant, who was here the whole life, except for some time at the Jefferson Bridge, and who had been hired by his father.

07:32.112 --> 07:35.035
And he was really like an aunt to the children.

07:35.690 --> 07:37.593
had died.

07:38.113 --> 07:55.758
And then Janet Eames, who's been at Mills College, who was a librarian for almost two years, she was working here in Arthur Freeman, who works at Quaritch in London, but is an American.

07:56.559 --> 07:58.782
She and Arthur got married, so she moved to London.

07:58.802 --> 08:02.527
And he was looking for it.

08:02.547 --> 08:04.850
And he said, you know, what I'd be interested.

08:04.870 --> 08:05.511
And I said, well,

08:05.980 --> 08:12.168
I didn't think that I was really what I wanted.

08:12.188 --> 08:13.390
First of all, I was a Canadian.

08:13.971 --> 08:15.994
I wasn't a librarian.

08:16.014 --> 08:21.862
I had a 10-year-old dream job, and that's why I sent my computer, and he worked something out.

08:21.882 --> 08:23.123
I was very, very happy.

08:23.143 --> 08:24.926
It'll be two years in July.

08:24.946 --> 08:26.588
It must be, if you love the book.

08:26.728 --> 08:28.591
Oh, it's wonderful.

08:28.691 --> 08:29.612
It's wonderful.

08:29.632 --> 08:30.894
It's wonderful.

08:30.914 --> 08:32.096
I mean, there's no castle.

08:32.116 --> 08:34.519
You're working for a very beautiful...

08:35.191 --> 08:38.674
I mean, it has it.

08:38.694 --> 08:39.315
Everything does.

08:39.495 --> 08:40.076
Everything does.

08:40.096 --> 08:42.598
I mean, you know, you work for one person, that's who you report to.

08:42.678 --> 08:46.201
If that one person's feeling grumpy, you have to put up with it.

08:46.982 --> 08:49.905
I mean, it has its advantage.

08:49.945 --> 08:55.430
I mean, I don't go to meetings, which is one of the biggest advantages.

08:55.450 --> 08:58.173
I mean, I enjoyed teaching, but I enjoyed research.

08:58.193 --> 08:59.954
You could teach a couple of courses here.

08:59.974 --> 09:02.797
Oh, then, yeah, I taught at night school here.

09:03.257 --> 09:03.898
I should think that

09:04.233 --> 09:15.809
Well, yeah, but this is Princeton, and they don't have to rush into anything too soon, so I'm sort of... How does this collection support scholarship?

09:15.889 --> 09:17.672
I think that's kind of the stipulation, right?

09:17.712 --> 09:20.436
Princeton agrees to this.

09:20.556 --> 09:24.101
I'm sure they agreed to it for the long term as well.

09:25.363 --> 09:30.730
However, I think they did say that...

09:31.233 --> 09:32.315
the research.

09:32.335 --> 09:32.936
Is that right?

09:32.976 --> 09:35.220
How does it support the scholarship?

09:35.700 --> 09:41.390
I mean, it's open to anybody with proper deliberation.

09:41.410 --> 09:49.964
The way that Princeton read books is open to anybody with proper deliberation.

09:49.984 --> 09:56.735
I mean, I had a student here this morning from Westminster Choir College, who's a student conducting the music.

09:56.755 --> 09:57.797
He wanted to look at

09:59.110 --> 10:03.174
And, you know, she registered as a reader with Princeton, and that's fine.

10:03.194 --> 10:05.876
And we let them in, and we look at them.

10:05.896 --> 10:06.897
The material stays here.

10:06.917 --> 10:19.588
The material stays here, or sometimes if I'm running around, I give it to Princeton, and they have a reading room, and somebody who watches the reading will keep traffic, but it counts the pages that go in, and counts the pages that go out.

10:20.189 --> 10:25.473
So it's much easier for me if I don't have to stay here and watch them.

10:25.493 --> 10:28.476
Do you ever discuss, I'll ask them,

10:29.671 --> 10:34.697
What's the future of the Shaggy collection?

10:34.717 --> 10:40.744
I mean, is this something that you're privy to?

10:40.924 --> 10:41.825
I know he has a daughter.

10:41.845 --> 10:46.010
He has two daughters and a son.

10:46.891 --> 10:48.053
I mean, I don't know what he'll tell you.

10:48.073 --> 10:58.345
I mean, obviously it's... Yeah, I mean, what he'll tell you is that maybe none of your business is going to answer that, but it'll go to Princeton.

10:59.675 --> 11:04.482
if his will stays the way it is.

11:04.522 --> 11:28.416
And the reason I would want to ask that question, certainly he must be mindful of exactly, it is, if it's not unique, the collection is three generations, but then I get this, I think, estate, and I'm sure Princeton has made all the necessaries

11:30.117 --> 11:33.782
assurances that it would be made as a shiny collection.

11:33.802 --> 11:35.724
It has for 25 years.

11:35.744 --> 11:39.649
I mean, it's no small expense on Princeton's part.

11:39.910 --> 11:46.999
I mean, he pays my salary, but they, you know, past support services are no small.

11:47.660 --> 11:50.944
Well, considering what they're getting, I suppose.

11:51.044 --> 11:54.629
But, I mean, you know, 25 years is a long time.

11:54.649 --> 11:57.593
Have you ever heard of such a new agent like this?

11:57.775 --> 11:59.417
Well, Princeton's done it before.

11:59.457 --> 12:02.740
You could talk to Bill Joyce or somebody.

12:02.760 --> 12:12.110
There's a man named Robert Taylor, who you may have heard of, and the Taylor Library is here in Princeton, in another part of their books.

12:12.130 --> 12:26.044
And Bob Taylor is particularly interested in English literature, moving, I think, more towards Victorian, but a big collection of Max Beerbund,

12:26.395 --> 12:27.577
and that kind of thing.

12:27.597 --> 12:30.601
And he had his library.

12:32.564 --> 12:35.528
I mean, there's a shitey room.

12:35.548 --> 12:37.631
There's a tailor room, and he felt it.

12:38.072 --> 12:43.019
And had a librarian who he paid, who worked here at New York before.

12:43.039 --> 12:48.307
And when he died, it became a tailor collection.

12:48.487 --> 12:56.098
I mean, it's only a local thing, but it's a library while the person is alive, and that becomes a collection.

12:56.382 --> 12:58.485
when they're done.

12:58.505 --> 13:10.002
But they, I mean, they still make, Taylor left money, and so they still make acquisitions.

13:10.022 --> 13:24.162
I was at the Morgan, I spent a couple hours at the Morgan yesterday, and I bought the Heinemann Collection, and it is, it does continue similarly as the Heinemann Collection, which they

13:24.817 --> 13:28.282
And that's very rich in music, by the way.

13:28.822 --> 13:31.626
I had not even heard of that collection before.

13:31.646 --> 13:33.428
I went to the illuminated manuscript.

13:33.448 --> 13:35.351
Oh yeah, the dust, that was just amazing.

13:35.371 --> 13:40.958
And the Morgan had those boxes up there, which are the envy of half the people in the museum world.

13:40.978 --> 13:41.359
That's right.

13:41.599 --> 13:48.588
And those are expensive to do, because they'd screw up this little wall, and then they'd take them off, and you'd fill the holes, and you'd paint or re-paper.

13:48.608 --> 13:51.752
But it does, as much, because the light's coming at you,

13:52.087 --> 13:53.209
It's almost like stained glass.

13:53.229 --> 13:54.671
Yeah, it's like stained glass.

13:54.891 --> 13:56.333
It's a hell of those things.

13:56.393 --> 14:06.808
I've interviewed one of the, the person who owns one of the manuscripts, Arthur Bruch-Boward, you know, have you ever heard about him?

14:06.828 --> 14:12.396
He and his wife are private collectors, and he's very quiet.

14:13.117 --> 14:15.580
I'm the first person they've ever talked to.

14:15.880 --> 14:23.850
He's the president of the Boston Athenaeum, his wife is president of the Friends of Holden Library, so that's very well-connected.

14:23.870 --> 14:28.376
And I'm sharing with Mr. Shady Wilson.

14:28.396 --> 14:31.159
I know him.

14:31.179 --> 14:40.010
But they have a very small collection, 1,000, 1,500, but... Yeah, oh yeah.

14:40.030 --> 14:42.073
That, I would think, the majority of people.

14:42.610 --> 14:48.257
who are collectors would be, I mean, it tends to be a manageable kind of side that you know.

14:48.277 --> 14:52.082
I mean, you also get, it seems, some fairly particular interests.

14:52.523 --> 14:56.989
I mean, there are very few people that collect on any kind of wide range.

14:57.009 --> 14:59.092
I think it's best to guess instead of part of sources.

14:59.112 --> 15:08.424
Yes, I mean, you get to know what makes something special.

15:08.444 --> 15:09.946
A series of collections.

15:10.847 --> 15:10.947
Yeah.

15:12.327 --> 15:37.115
you know, Princeton has the Junius Morgan collection of Virgil, and the so-and-so, the Patterson collection of Horvath, and somebody's collection of Ernest Hemingway, and somebody's, you know, they tend to just, having, I think, there's something about book collectors, having spent the time focusing on that material, getting it all together, and having made notes and records of how it all relates.

15:37.135 --> 15:38.096
And getting the best copies.

15:38.116 --> 15:41.760
And getting the best copies available, then to say,

15:43.563 --> 15:45.525
You know, I don't care what happens to it.

15:45.546 --> 15:47.588
Let's have a big auction and let it be dispersed again.

15:47.608 --> 15:48.429
Well, some say that.

15:48.489 --> 15:49.190
Some say that.

15:49.210 --> 15:50.231
I mean, that's what Bradley Martin said.

15:50.251 --> 15:51.673
Bradley Martin said it.

15:51.693 --> 15:55.979
And there's a famous quote by Robert Hull, who was one of the fonds.

15:56.820 --> 15:58.342
I have the catalog of it.

15:58.362 --> 16:01.586
It's Beverly Chew closing in the introduction.

16:01.606 --> 16:01.946
Yeah.

16:02.046 --> 16:04.870
If it weren't for collectors, where would I have gotten that?

16:05.030 --> 16:09.997
And I want to return it so other collectors could have the fun that I had or something along those lines.

16:10.918 --> 16:12.760
But that's a fairly rare...

16:14.039 --> 16:21.926
I mean, most people kind of see it as some kind of monument or something that they've worked on and they want it to remain intact.

16:21.946 --> 16:28.993
Well, if it's a really exceptional collection, as this is, that is not likely to be replicated.

16:29.013 --> 16:29.714
No, no.

16:29.914 --> 16:30.595
That's the problem.

16:30.755 --> 16:38.282
But, I mean, that's why when you mentioned this collector in Newton, you know, that they have a kind of small choice.

16:38.522 --> 16:43.607
I was at their houses a couple of weeks ago and took out this

16:44.093 --> 16:45.395
Book of Hours.

16:46.517 --> 16:48.800
It was beautiful, and it illuminated stuff.

16:48.820 --> 16:51.224
And he said, but no, he said, read the inscription.

16:51.324 --> 16:54.209
Well, it was, pray for me as I pray for you.

16:54.329 --> 17:04.945
It was an inscribed, an inscribed Book of Hours from Henry VIII to a woman named Margaret Cole, who I believe, I'm not sure later, was beheaded.

17:05.065 --> 17:09.132
Well, Cole certainly was one of the archbishops of Canada.

17:09.152 --> 17:10.714
I mean, there was a Jewish family.

17:10.734 --> 17:12.717
Yeah, and this was a script.

17:13.861 --> 17:15.804
I'm holding it.

17:16.785 --> 17:19.488
That's really quite extraordinary.

17:19.549 --> 17:21.351
Well, we couldn't afford it today, I'm sure.

17:21.451 --> 17:23.934
You know, that's what most people say.

17:25.236 --> 17:27.319
Prices have gotten so high.

17:27.339 --> 17:34.628
And that's why, I mean, Mr. Scheide alone couldn't have done it today.

17:34.648 --> 17:37.432
I mean, he relies on his grandfather, in particular on his father.

17:38.233 --> 17:41.117
And that's why people collect

17:42.498 --> 17:44.540
kind of less broadly than practice.

17:44.560 --> 17:57.233
Or they, you know, they tend to collect, you know, not the original material, but, you know, not manuscript material, but first editions.

17:57.253 --> 18:02.258
Or they collect modern authors, assuming that a hundred years from now.

18:02.278 --> 18:04.000
Sure.

18:04.901 --> 18:08.184
Now, are you bitten by the collecting bug at all?

18:08.204 --> 18:08.425
No.

18:08.565 --> 18:11.728
I just seem to find that they're the professionals who work

18:12.603 --> 18:14.185
I can't understand this stuff.

18:14.465 --> 18:25.259
No, I mean, I am, in a sense, I mean, I want to acquire things for the Shady Library, but not for myself.

18:26.341 --> 18:34.772
I mean, I'm interested in books as historical objects, but in a sense, once I know about it, it doesn't make any difference to me where it is.

18:34.792 --> 18:36.855
Are you working actively in... Yeah.

18:37.115 --> 18:42.542
...perspective... Yeah, I mean, we just thought of...

18:43.163 --> 18:48.712
of an interesting manuscript in a book.

18:48.732 --> 18:53.820
Manuscripts that were written and then used as printer's copy.

18:53.840 --> 19:01.071
So we bought a copy of the book with the manuscript.

19:01.091 --> 19:08.243
There were about 15 of those.

19:08.263 --> 19:09.144
Yeah, I mean, it's great.

19:09.184 --> 19:11.027
That's the exciting thing.

19:11.260 --> 19:14.164
I mean, that's a whole new aspect of it.

19:16.027 --> 19:17.569
What is the portal name of this room?

19:17.589 --> 19:18.830
Does it have a portal name?

19:18.850 --> 19:20.533
No, it's called The Shady Library.

19:20.793 --> 19:25.560
It's called The Shady Library.

19:25.580 --> 19:28.223
Your access is from the library.

19:28.243 --> 19:34.572
And there's also that door there, which goes to the other side, so that I come in on the weekends and Saturdays.

19:34.892 --> 19:38.297
Because, of course, it's all alarmed, both there and there.

19:38.851 --> 19:40.613
It's very safe here, too, I would imagine.

19:40.653 --> 19:43.996
It is in a night wave.

19:44.016 --> 19:49.882
It's beautiful.

19:49.902 --> 19:56.468
And at a certain stage, it just gets too valuable or too important to keep in your home.

19:57.730 --> 20:01.654
And that's when you have to kind of move to an institution.

