42:53.023 --> 42:59.171
It's in that scene around Act IV or so, where Laertes comes back and tries to start a rebellion.

42:59.251 --> 43:00.513
Remember that scene, more or less?

43:01.174 --> 43:03.137
And what's his name?

43:03.217 --> 43:06.241
Claudius and his wife, or queen, are talking about it.

43:07.062 --> 43:07.463
Gertrude.

43:07.763 --> 43:09.145
Yeah.

43:09.165 --> 43:12.810
They're talking about it, and there's a remark that he makes to her in that dialogue.

43:13.583 --> 43:15.065
So there it is.

43:15.385 --> 43:16.146
Hugger-mugger.

43:16.486 --> 43:17.087
Yeah, hugger-mugger.

43:17.888 --> 43:22.853
But now he's going to, he's going to, now he resolves to keep this book and so forth.

43:22.873 --> 43:26.016
And then he goes on and has a great time about Queen Elizabeth here.

43:26.036 --> 43:28.980
It's a small thing.

43:29.000 --> 43:41.413
Yeah, Lady, Queen, and all, and all die before the sorrowful days of England shall come if God should take her.

43:42.659 --> 43:45.403
take her from us, I think, before the end of the world.

43:47.145 --> 44:09.477
And if for our sins she should die, I suppose, I can't remember all these words, but whether something of God, that I pray God or something, that he will grant me the grace to die at her feet before her.

44:10.773 --> 44:12.635
That's what this guy wants to do.

44:14.217 --> 44:15.519
She's going to die sometime.

44:15.539 --> 44:16.920
He wants to die at her feet before.

44:16.960 --> 44:18.682
Actually, she'd be a little bit surprised.

44:20.565 --> 44:22.367
Die at her feet before.

44:22.407 --> 44:29.375
And the last days, well, anyway, he put an everlasting life.

44:29.435 --> 44:30.837
Amen, amen.

44:31.137 --> 44:32.699
He's in a great state.

44:32.819 --> 44:37.084
I just think a scholar would find some very interesting material in there about

44:38.110 --> 44:39.573
temporary life.

44:39.593 --> 44:40.034
Sure.

44:40.695 --> 44:42.920
It's one of the important books.

44:44.242 --> 44:55.344
I mean, there's a whole, there was a kind of myth going, that Lollards were kind of an underground group, and therefore the manuscripts which they produced therefore ought to be kind of homemade products.

44:55.525 --> 44:55.845
I see.

44:55.906 --> 44:57.148
Well, you just look at that,

44:58.107 --> 44:59.930
And you know that isn't a homemade product.

45:00.010 --> 45:01.131
That, for sure.

45:02.093 --> 45:06.298
Well, it's no really fancy one, but it's an incredible job.

45:06.358 --> 45:07.160
It's an incredible job.

45:07.200 --> 45:09.122
And they all look the same.

45:09.283 --> 45:13.248
I mean, all kind of... Some of them are pretty fibery.

45:13.268 --> 45:15.111
They're very much fancier ones.

45:15.151 --> 45:15.892
Not much, though.

45:15.952 --> 45:16.833
Oh, yes.

45:16.853 --> 45:18.455
It's a much bigger book.

45:18.515 --> 45:19.196
Look at those.

45:19.236 --> 45:21.339
Those are almost illuminations there, aren't they?

45:21.860 --> 45:25.465
The Kenworth.

45:26.255 --> 45:30.239
I saw the show yesterday at the Morgan, by the way, on the Dutch manuscripts.

45:30.259 --> 45:31.260
Imaginary, lovely.

45:31.280 --> 45:32.120
It's quite beautiful.

45:32.360 --> 45:35.844
The Times has been doing it this week until Sunday.

45:35.904 --> 45:37.225
They're going to do it on Sunday?

45:37.265 --> 45:38.106
Yeah.

45:38.126 --> 45:40.788
All right, I'll have an eye for it.

45:40.808 --> 45:42.049
We'll go up and take a look next week.

45:42.329 --> 45:43.971
It's really quite wonderful.

45:44.632 --> 45:46.393
Yeah, these letters.

45:46.413 --> 45:47.714
Some of these Sauter ones.

45:48.555 --> 45:50.817
These are the Psalms, you see, the Sauter, he says.

45:50.857 --> 45:52.318
This is something your father acquired?

45:52.359 --> 45:52.719
Yeah.

45:53.179 --> 45:56.262
How old were you when you became aware of the contents of this book?

45:56.798 --> 46:00.444
Oh, I remember more as when it came, I guess, in 1931.

46:02.247 --> 46:06.134
Did you always share the same enthusiasm for the books that your father did?

46:06.154 --> 46:08.618
No, he sort of took them for granted.

46:08.938 --> 46:12.785
I mean, but at what point did you realize that this was a generational legacy?

46:12.845 --> 46:17.373
I mean, it was almost a responsibility to this extraordinary collection.

46:18.134 --> 46:21.199
Yeah, it was part of the atmosphere I grew up in.

46:22.261 --> 46:23.042
I knew nothing about that.

46:24.743 --> 46:29.629
There's, for example, the Competentian Polyglot up there.

46:29.649 --> 46:33.975
It isn't everybody that has that right under his playroom.

46:34.055 --> 46:35.878
Now, which did we say that was?

46:35.898 --> 46:37.239
Competentian Polyglot?

46:37.860 --> 46:42.386
Oh, that's a—think of Steve Wiseman, who runs Simony's bookshop.

46:42.706 --> 46:44.689
That's the fellow that published his thing.

46:44.789 --> 46:45.230
Okay.

46:45.991 --> 46:53.080
And—I mean, you remember— You don't have to get it out, but— You remember the books coming to the house.

46:53.347 --> 46:54.568
Well, I don't remember that book.

46:54.629 --> 46:56.771
No, but I remember this book.

46:56.791 --> 47:00.195
I remember the Gutenberg Bible, Big Bucks, by Dr. Rosenbach.

47:00.676 --> 47:01.036
Really?

47:01.096 --> 47:02.658
Earlier in 1924.

47:06.342 --> 47:08.725
Well, there you get an idea.

47:08.745 --> 47:09.846
But that is a unique one.

47:09.866 --> 47:11.428
You can't see that anywhere else in this country.

47:11.869 --> 47:21.480
Speaking of Rosenbach, when I was talking to Ed Wolff, I never thought I'd hear him say that he actually thought that when it came to knowledge of books that Klaus was just

47:21.747 --> 47:24.510
superior to Rosenbach in terms of knowledge of books.

47:24.851 --> 47:26.012
And this is both.

47:26.072 --> 47:30.377
Rosenbach, on the other hand, was more of a friend, you know, more of a hardy good fellow.

47:30.597 --> 47:37.065
He said when it actually came to knowledge of books, I wonder if you'd have any thoughts on either of those two.

47:37.105 --> 47:49.459
Well, Ed would have known Rosenbach very much better than I. I only saw him very occasionally as a boy or a young person and worked with him and was educated by him.

47:50.063 --> 47:55.768
I couldn't believe it, but I certainly couldn't argue with that point.

47:55.828 --> 48:00.633
It's very interesting you never said that.

48:00.653 --> 48:02.174
Well, Hanson will get mixed up now and then.

48:04.436 --> 48:09.301
Show me the thing we want to have a facsimile of.

48:11.663 --> 48:13.945
And this is a really interesting story.

48:14.826 --> 48:16.948
And if we can ever get

48:17.587 --> 48:20.711
and Hope Mayo to do the job.

48:21.452 --> 48:39.697
And now this is, there is a, there is a, um, this is a papal bull printed in Mainz in probably late 1456, and this is a Latin copy.

48:40.759 --> 48:46.767
There is a German copy of it, and printed in the same type, probably about the same time, in Berlin.

48:47.590 --> 48:53.199
But this is the only printed version, contemporary printed version, in Latin, you see.

48:54.101 --> 48:59.149
And this is the earlier Gutenberg type, the 36-line size.

48:59.991 --> 49:05.119
And there's probably more 36-line type in this room than there is anywhere else in this country.

49:06.862 --> 49:08.144
And most of it's here.

49:08.204 --> 49:09.647
Well, the 42 is first, right?

49:09.887 --> 49:11.590
You need to do the 42 and then...

49:11.890 --> 49:12.330
Well.

49:12.871 --> 49:14.553
We don't know that.

49:14.573 --> 49:14.793
Okay.

49:14.853 --> 49:16.935
The 42 was used for the first big book.

49:17.195 --> 49:18.056
Okay.

49:18.076 --> 49:18.857
First, first book.

49:18.917 --> 49:19.878
Which comes first, though?

49:19.898 --> 49:22.481
This, the other, the 42 comes first, right?

49:22.501 --> 49:22.661
No?

49:24.343 --> 49:28.287
Before the, for the, the, the Bible, there's a prehistory.

49:28.507 --> 49:29.488
It's speculated.

49:30.109 --> 49:31.810
My guess is that this is earlier.

49:31.830 --> 49:38.217
That this is on the, on the road to, um, they kept reducing the size, I think.

49:40.079 --> 49:40.159
Hmm.

49:40.628 --> 49:47.776
It does stretch credulity to think that printing emerges full-blown with the 42-line Bible.

49:47.796 --> 49:50.619
That's too much for me.

49:50.859 --> 49:56.666
And this type, now there are all kinds of funny pieces of type here.

49:56.686 --> 49:58.688
Let me see if I can find one of my favorite pieces.

49:58.708 --> 49:59.909
It's beautiful though, isn't it?

49:59.929 --> 50:01.130
Well, there's some nice letters in here.

50:01.791 --> 50:08.138
Where's he, when he talks, look at that, look at that tree there, how that's well-eat.

50:08.793 --> 50:13.317
That boy we're talking about, actually, instead of tree, right?

50:13.337 --> 50:15.279
Look at the bell ringing, you see.

50:16.800 --> 50:17.581
Isn't that wonderful?

50:17.601 --> 50:19.863
Una campana sonorosa.

50:21.805 --> 50:26.469
The Pope wants bells ringing very sonorously.

50:26.489 --> 50:27.290
What do we call this?

50:27.991 --> 50:29.352
Calixtus Bull, we'll call it.

50:29.993 --> 50:31.914
What's the Pope calling this?

50:32.435 --> 50:33.296
Bull on a turk, see.

50:33.376 --> 50:34.116
Bull on a turk, see.

50:34.136 --> 50:36.619
There comes Calixtus, a bishop.

50:36.819 --> 50:38.040
C-A-L-I.

50:38.830 --> 50:43.556
Well, he spells it there with an S. It's sometimes spelled with an X. Either will pass.

50:43.576 --> 50:43.776
Okay.

50:44.197 --> 50:45.098
We want to be accurate.

50:45.478 --> 50:45.779
Yes.

50:46.179 --> 50:49.183
Now, this is something, again, that your father... Yes, yes.

50:50.044 --> 50:55.471
And Mr. Krause has had various attitudes about this book.

50:55.491 --> 50:58.435
You see there, it's been taken out of something.

50:58.635 --> 50:59.216
Can you see that?

51:01.458 --> 51:08.247
And my father got it in 39, and...

51:08.868 --> 51:12.836
I talked to Krause about this, and he knew about the sale.

51:13.577 --> 51:15.260
It was a sale in Prague, I think.

51:16.683 --> 51:21.793
I forget the name of the nobleman who was having no more at that time.

51:22.534 --> 51:27.484
But Krause said, oh, one time he said,

51:27.886 --> 51:29.528
Oh, I was a young fellow.

51:29.588 --> 51:32.090
I didn't know anything.

51:32.110 --> 51:34.112
I had this bread in my possession.

51:34.272 --> 51:36.034
I didn't know what I had.

51:36.094 --> 51:37.535
He's crying a little bit, right?

51:37.836 --> 51:38.396
Oh, yes.

51:38.416 --> 51:43.661
Another time, he didn't admit that and didn't think it was he at all.

51:44.162 --> 51:50.127
But somebody took it from there and got it to Mag somehow or other, and my father could never get to the bottom of it.

51:50.307 --> 51:51.208
Is that completed?

51:51.649 --> 51:51.949
Yes.

51:52.069 --> 51:53.531
That's not a leaf or anything?

51:53.611 --> 51:55.092
No, see, there's an end of it.

51:55.578 --> 51:56.680
There's the beginning of it.

51:56.700 --> 51:57.240
There's the end of it.

51:57.260 --> 51:57.921
So how many pages?

51:59.484 --> 52:02.428
Well, I numbered them one time as 10A, 10B.

52:02.608 --> 52:06.354
So there would be 20 pages, rather small pages.

52:06.374 --> 52:09.558
And I'm trying to find a particular page.

52:11.501 --> 52:13.324
You can tell particular pieces of type.

52:13.805 --> 52:24.420
This U, for example, has a gap in a certain place, and another U that has it in a different injury in another place.

52:25.177 --> 52:29.161
And that's my favorite—well, I guess this is the place.

52:29.181 --> 52:37.289
There's a—and that T, that was a—that crops up lots of places.

52:37.750 --> 52:40.072
That almost looks like it's been filled in, doesn't it?

52:40.612 --> 52:40.833
Where?

52:40.853 --> 52:41.173
I wonder.

52:41.814 --> 52:42.895
What's been filled in?

52:42.915 --> 52:47.399
It doesn't, but I mean, it looks like maybe they went over it, or do you think— No, it's bad inking there.

52:47.419 --> 52:48.060
It's bad inking there.

52:48.520 --> 52:48.781
Yeah.

52:49.141 --> 52:50.162
But you see—look at this.

52:50.182 --> 52:52.244
You see the watermark right there without any trouble at all.

52:52.264 --> 52:52.644
Indeed.

52:53.005 --> 52:54.306
Great impression.

52:54.539 --> 53:00.085
Now here, you see there's a T with a very wide crossbar.

53:01.127 --> 53:03.129
Very different than that T there, for example.

53:03.850 --> 53:04.731
Very narrow crossbar.

53:05.131 --> 53:07.154
Has there been a study of the type made?

53:07.214 --> 53:09.877
Is it Kusenberg's type?

53:09.977 --> 53:10.317
Oh, no, no.

53:10.357 --> 53:12.420
Paul Needham's been over every single letter in this.

53:12.760 --> 53:15.503
This O is also unique, I think, to this room.

53:16.044 --> 53:17.285
There's a hole down there.

53:18.727 --> 53:19.148
Wow!

53:19.648 --> 53:20.890
I'm going to write that one down.

53:20.930 --> 53:22.892
Well, I don't know.

53:23.513 --> 53:25.017
I said the Anglo-Saxon also.

53:25.057 --> 53:25.559
Yeah.

53:26.622 --> 53:28.327
Well, there may be another one of it.

53:28.407 --> 53:30.533
That might be the title of this chapter, by the way.

53:30.554 --> 53:30.754
Yes.

